  "companies": [],
  "statement": "# Swim in Rising Water\n\nReturn the earliest time when a path exists from the top-left to bottom-right cell in a grid whose values are water levels.\n\n## Examples\n\n**Example 1**\n\n```text\nInput: grid = [[0,2],[1,3]]\nOutput: 3\n```\n\n**Example 2**\n\n```text\nInput: grid = [[0,1,2],[5,4,3],[6,7,8]]\nOutput: 8\n```\n\n**Example 3**\n\n```text\nInput: grid = [[7]]\nOutput: 7\n```\n\n## Constraints\n\n- Inputs are sized for local offline execution.\n- Return values follow the method description.",
  "editorial": "Use the graph structure directly: traverse reachable states, maintain visited or distance state, and update the answer when each node or cell is settled.",
  "solution_notes": "```python\nimport heapq\n\nclass Solution:\n    def swimInWater(self, grid):\n        n = len(grid)\n        heap = [(grid[0][0], 0, 0)]\n        seen = set()\n        while heap:\n            time, r, c = heapq.heappop(heap)\n            if (r, c) in seen: continue\n            seen.add((r, c))\n            if r == n - 1 and c == n - 1: return time\n            for dr, dc in ((1,0),(-1,0),(0,1),(0,-1)):\n                nr, nc = r + dr, c + dc\n                if 0 <= nr < n and 0 <= nc < n and (nr, nc) not in seen:\n                    heapq.heappush(heap, (max(time, grid[nr][nc]), nr, nc))\n```",
  "hints": [
    "Model the state explicitly.",
    "Prefer linear or near-linear graph traversal when possible."
  ],
